
[1]safe

   SAFE, a. [L. salvus, from salus, safety, health.]

   1. Free from danger of any kind; as safe from enemies; safe from
   disease; safe from storms; safe from the malice of foes.

   2. Free from hurt, injury or damage; as, to walk safe over red hot
   plowshares. We brought the goods safe to land.

   3. Conferring safety; securing from harm; as a safe guide; a safe
   harbor; a safe bridge.

   4. Not exposing to danger. Phil. 3.

   5. No longer dangerous; placed beyond the power of doing harm; a
   ludicrous meaning.

   Banquo's safe. - Aye, my good lord, safe in a ditch.

      SAFE, n. A place of safety; a place for securing provisions from
                              noxious animals.

                  SAFE, v.t. To render safe. [Not in use.]
